cklish-plotting-starfish\",\"type\":\"progress\",\"data\":{\"message\":{\"type\":\"user\",\"message\":{\"role\":\"user\",\"content\":[{\"tool_use_id\":\"toolu_011JkM5oXH9CPYGXWNbv9n7Z\",\"type\":\"tool_result\",\"content\":\"   200→if s.Enabled {\\n   201→    // ...\\n   202→}\\n   203→\\n   204→// Or use convenience functions\\n   205→if settings.IsSummarizeEnabled() {\\n   206→    // ...\\n   207→}\\n   208→```\\n   209→\\n   210→**Do NOT:**\\n   211→\\n   212→- Read `.entire/settings.json` or `.entire/settings.local.json` directly with `os.ReadFile`\\n   213→- Duplicate settings parsing logic in other packages\\n   214→- Create new settings helpers without adding them to the `settings` package\\n   215→\\n   216→**Key files:**\\n   217→\\n   218→- `settings/settings.go` - `EntireSettings` struct, `Load()`, and helper methods\\n   219→- `config.go` - Higher-level config functions that use settings (for `cli` package consumers)\\n   220→\\n   221→### Logging vs User Output\\n   222→\\n   223→- **Internal/debug logging**: Use `logging.Debug/Info/Warn/Error(ctx, msg, attrs...)` from `cmd/entire/cli/logging/`. Writes to `.entire/logs/`.\\n   224→- **User-facing output**: Use `fmt.Fprint*(cmd.OutOrStdout(), ...)` or `cmd.ErrOrStderr()`.\\n   225→\\n   226→Don't use `fmt.Print*` for operational messages (checkpoint saves, hook invocations, strategy decisions) - those should use the `logging` package.\\n   227→\\n   228→**Privacy**: Don't log user content (prompts, file contents, commit messages). Log only operational metadata (IDs, counts, paths, durations).\\n   229→\\n   230→### Git Operations\\n   231→\\n   232→We use github.com/go-git/go-git for most git operations, but with important exceptions:\\n   233→\\n   234→#### go-git v5 Bugs - Use CLI Instead\\n   235→\\n   236→**Do NOT use go-git v5 for `checkout` or `reset --hard` operations.**\\n   237→\\n   238→go-git v5 has a bug where `worktree.Reset()` with `git.HardReset` and `worktree.Checkout()` incorrectly delete untracked directories even when they're listed in `.gitignore`. This would destroy `.entire/` and `.worktrees/` directories.\\n   239→\\n   240→Use the git CLI instead:\\n   241→\\n   242→```go\\n   243→// WRONG - go-git deletes ignored directories\\n   244→worktree.Reset(&git.ResetOptions{\\n   245→    Commit: hash,\\n   246→    Mode:   git.HardReset,\\n   247→})\\n   248→\\n   249→// CORRECT - use git CLI\\n   250→cmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \\\"git\\\", \\\"reset\\\", \\\"--hard\\\", hash.String())\\n   251→```\\n   252→\\n   253→See `HardResetWithProtection()` in `common.go` and `CheckoutBranch()` in `git_operations.go` for examples.\\n   254→\\n   255→Regression tests in `hard_reset_test.go` verify this behavior - if go-git v6 fixes this issue, those tests can be used to validate switching back.\\n   256→\\n   257→#### Repo Root vs Current Working Directory\\n   258→\\n   259→**Always use repo root (not `os.Getwd()`) when working with git-relative paths.**\\n   260→\\n   261→Git commands like `git status` and `worktree.Status()` return paths relative to the **repository root**, not the current working directory. When an agent runs from a subdirectory (e.g., `/repo/frontend`), using `os.Getwd()` to construct absolute paths will produce incorrect results for files in sibling directories.\\n   262→\\n   263→```go\\n   264→// WRONG - breaks when running from subdirectory\\n   265→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // e.g., /repo/frontend\\n   266→absPath := filepath.Join(cwd, file)  // file=\\\"api/src/types.ts\\\" → /repo/frontend/api/src/types.ts (WRONG)\\n   267→\\n   268→// CORRECT - use repo root\\n   269→repoRoot, _ := paths.WorktreeRoot()\\n   270→absPath := filepath.Join(repoRoot, file)  // → /repo/api/src/types.ts (CORRECT)\\n   271→```\\n   272→\\n   273→This also affects path filtering. The `paths.ToRelativePath()` function rejects paths starting with `..`, so computing relative paths from cwd instead of repo root will filter out files in sibling directories:\\n   274→\\n   275→```go\\n   276→// WRONG - filters out sibling directory files\\n   277→cwd, _ := os.Getwd()  // /repo/frontend\\n   278→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", cwd)  // returns \\\"\\\" (filtered out as \\\"../api/file.ts\\\")\\n   279→\\n   280→// CORRECT - keeps all repo files\\n   281→repoRoot, _ := paths.WorktreeRoot()\\n   282→relPath := paths.ToRelativePath(\\\"/repo/api/file.ts\\\", repoRoot)  // returns \\\"api/file.ts\\\"\\n   283→```\\n   284→\\n   285→**When to use `os.Getwd()`:** Only when you actually need the current directory (e.g., finding agent session directories that are cwd-relative).\\n   286→\\n   287→**When to use repo root:** Any time you're working with paths from git status, git diff, or any git-relative file list.\\n   288→\\n   289→Test case in `state_test.go`: `TestFilterAndNormalizePaths_SiblingDirectories` documents this bug pattern.\\n   290→\\n   291→### Session Strategy (`cmd/entire/cli/strategy/`)\\n   292→\\n   293→The CLI uses a manual-commit strategy for managing session data and checkpoints. The strategy implements the `Strategy` interface defined in `strategy.go`.\\n   294→\\n   295→#### Strategy Interface\\n   296→\\n   297→The `Strategy` interface provides:\\n   298→\\n   299→- `SaveStep()` - Save session step checkpoint (code + metadata)\\n   300→- `SaveTaskStep()` - Save subagent task step checkpoint\\n   301→- `GetRewindPoints()` / `Rewind()` - List and restore to checkpoints\\n   302→- `GetSessionLog()` / `GetSessionInfo()` - Retrieve session data\\n   303→- `ListSessions()` / `GetSession()` - Session discovery\\n   304→\\n   305→#### How It Works\\n   306→\\n   307→The manual-commit strategy (`manual_commit*.go`) does not modify the active branch - no commits are created on the working branch. Instead it:\\n   308→\\n   309→- Creates shadow branch `entire/<HEAD-commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>` per base commit + worktree\\n   310→- **Worktree-specific branches** - each git worktree gets its own shadow branch namespace, preventing conflicts\\n   311→- **Supports multiple concurrent sessions** - checkpoints from different sessions in the same directory interleave on the same shadow branch\\n   312→- Condenses session logs to permanent `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch on user commits\\n   313→- Builds git trees in-memory using go-git plumbing APIs\\n   314→- Rewind restores files from shadow branch commit tree (does not use `git reset`)\\n   315→- **Location-independent transcript resolution** - transcript paths are always computed dynamically from the current repo location (via `agent.GetSessionDir` + `agent.ResolveSessionFile`), never stored in checkpoint metadata. This ensures restore/rewind works after repo relocation or across machines.\\n   316→- Tracks session state in `.git/entire-sessions/` (shared across worktrees)\\n   317→- **Shadow branch migration** - if user does stash/pull/rebase (HEAD changes without commit), shadow branch is automatically moved to new base commit\\n   318→- **Orphaned branch cleanup** - if a shadow branch exists without a corresponding session state file, it is automatically reset when a new session starts\\n   319→- PrePush hook can push `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch alongside user pushes\\n   320→- Safe to use on main/master since it never modifies commit history\\n   321→\\n   322→#### Key Files\\n   323→\\n   324→- `strategy.go` - Interface definition and context structs (`StepContext`, `TaskStepContext`, `RewindPoint`, etc.)\\n   325→- `common.go` - Helpers for metadata extraction, tree building, rewind validation, `ListCheckpoints()`\\n   326→- `session.go` - Session/checkpoint data structures\\n   327→- `push_common.go` - PrePush logic for pushing `entire/checkpoints/v1` branch\\n   328→- `manual_commit.go` - Manual-commit strategy main implementation\\n   329→- `manual_commit_types.go` - Type definitions: `SessionState`, `CheckpointInfo`, `CondenseResult`\\n   330→- `manual_commit_session.go` - Session state management (load/save/list session states)\\n   331→- `manual_commit_condensation.go` - Condense logic for copying logs to `entire/checkpoints/v1`\\n   332→- `manual_commit_rewind.go` - Rewind implementation: file restoration from checkpoint trees\\n   333→- `manual_commit_git.go` - Git operations: checkpoint commits, tree building\\n   334→- `manual_commit_logs.go` - Session log retrieval and session listing\\n   335→- `manual_commit_hooks.go` - Git hook handlers (prepare-commit-msg, post-commit, pre-push)\\n   336→- `manual_commit_reset.go` - Shadow branch reset/cleanup functionality\\n   337→- `session_state.go` - Package-level session state functions (`LoadSessionState`, `SaveSessionState`, `ListSessionStates`, `FindMostRecentSession`)\\n   338→- `hooks.go` - Git hook installation\\n   339→\\n   340→#### Checkpoint Package (`cmd/entire/cli/checkpoint/`)\\n   341→\\n   342→- `checkpoint.go` - Data types (`Checkpoint`, `TemporaryCheckpoint`, `CommittedCheckpoint`)\\n   343→- `store.go` - `GitStore` struct wrapping git repository\\n   344→- `temporary.go` - Shadow branch operations (`WriteTemporary`, `ReadTemporary`, `ListTemporary`)\\n   345→- `committed.go` - Metadata branch operations (`WriteCommitted`, `ReadCommitted`, `ListCommitted`)\\n   346→\\n   347→#### Session Package (`cmd/entire/cli/session/`)\\n   348→\\n   349→- `session.go` - Session data types and interfaces\\n   350→- `state.go` - `StateStore` for managing `.git/entire-sessions/` files\\n   351→- `phase.go` - Session phase state machine (phases, events, transitions, actions)\\n   352→\\n   353→#### Session Phase State Machine\\n   354→\\n   355→Sessions track their lifecycle through phases managed by a state machine in `session/phase.go`:\\n   356→\\n   357→**Phases:** `ACTIVE`, `IDLE`, `ENDED`\\n   358→\\n   359→**Events:**\\n   360→\\n   361→- `TurnStart` - Agent begins a turn (UserPromptSubmit hook)\\n   362→- `TurnEnd` - Agent finishes a turn (Stop hook)\\n   363→- `GitCommit` - A git commit was made (PostCommit hook)\\n   364→- `SessionStart` - New session started\\n   365→- `SessionStop` - Session explicitly stopped\\n   366→\\n   367→**Key transitions:**\\n   368→\\n   369→- `IDLE + TurnStart → ACTIVE` - Agent starts working\\n   370→- `ACTIVE + TurnEnd → IDLE` - Agent finishes turn\\n   371→- `ACTIVE + GitCommit → ACTIVE` - User commits while agent is working (condense immediately)\\n   372→- `IDLE + GitCommit → IDLE` - User commits between turns (condense immediately)\\n   373→- `ENDED + GitCommit → ENDED` - Post-session commit (condense if files touched)\\n   374→\\n   375→The state machine emits **actions** (e.g., `ActionCondense`, `ActionUpdateLastInteraction`) that hook handlers dispatch to strategy-specific implementations.\\n   376→\\n   377→#### Metadata Structure\\n   378→\\n   379→**Shadow branches** (`entire/<commit-hash[:7]>-<worktreeHash[:6]>`):\\n   380→\\n   381→```\\n   382→.entire/metadata/<session-id>/\\n   383→├── full.jsonl               # Session transcript\\n   384→├── prompt.txt               # User prompts\\n   385→├── context.md               # Generated context\\n   386→└── tasks/<tool-use-id>/     # Task checkpoints\\n   387→    ├── checkpoint.json      # UUID mapping for rewind\\n   388→    └── agent-<id>.jsonl     # Subagent transcript\\n   389→```\\n   390→\\n   391→**Metadata branch** (`entire/checkpoints/v1`) - sharded checkpoint format:\\n   392→\\n   393→```\\n   394→<checkpoint-id[:2]>/<checkpoint-id[2:]>/\\n   395→├── metadata.json            # CheckpointSummary (aggregated stats)\\n   396→├── 0/                       # First session (0-based indexing)\\n   397→│   ├── metadata.json        # Session-specific metadata\\n   398→│   ├── full.jsonl           # Session transcript\\n   399→│   ├── prompt.txt           # User prompts\\n   400→│   ├── context.md           # Generated context\\n   401→│   ├── content_hash.txt     # SHA256 of transcript\\n   402→│   └── tasks/<tool-use-id>/ # Task checkpoints (if applicable)\\n   403→│       ├── checkpoint.json  # UUID mapping\\n   404→│       └── agent-<id>.jsonl # Subagent transcript\\n   405→├── 1/                       # Second session (if multiple sessions)\\n   406→│   ├── metadata.json\\n   407→│   ├── full.jsonl\\n   408→│   └── ...\\n   409→└── ...\\n   410→```\\n   411→\\n   412→**Multi-session metadata.json format:**\\n   413→\\n   414→```json\\n   415→{\\n   416→  \\\"checkpoint_id\\\": \\\"abc123def456\\\",\\n   417→  \\\"session_id\\\": \\\"2026-01-13-uuid\\\", // Current/latest session\\n   418→  \\\"session_ids\\\": [\\\"2026-01-13-uuid1\\\", \\\"2026-01-13-uuid2\\\"], // All sessions\\n   419→  \\\"session_count\\\": 2, // Number of sessions in this checkpoint\\n   420→  \\\"strategy\\\": \\\"manual-commit\\\",\\n   421→  \\\"created_at\\\": \\\"2026-01-13T12:00:00Z\\\",\\n   422→  \\\"files_touched\\\": [\\\"file1.txt\\\", \\\"file2.txt\\\"] // Merged from all sessions\\n   423→}\\n   424→```\\n   425→\\n   426→When multiple sessions are condensed to the same checkpoint (same base commit):\\n   427→\\n   428→- Sessions are stored in numbered subfolders using 0-based indexing (`0/`, `1/`, `2/`, etc.)\\n   429→- Latest session is always in the highest-numbered folder\\n   430→- `session_ids` array tracks all sessions, `session_count` increments\\n   431→\\n   432→**Session State** (filesystem, `.git/entire-sessions/`):\\n   433→\\n   434→```\\n   435→<session-id>.json            # Active session state (base_commit, checkpoint_count, etc.)\\n   436→```\\n   437→\\n   438→#### Checkpoint ID Linking\\n   439→\\n   440→The strategy uses a **12-hex-char random checkpoint ID** (e.g., `a3b2c4d5e6f7`) as the stable identifier linking user commits to metadata.\\n   441→\\n   442→**How checkpoint IDs work:**\\n   443→\\n   444→1. **Generated once per checkpoint**: When condensing session metadata to the metadata branch\\n   445→\\n   446→2. **Added to user commits** via `Entire-Checkpoint` trailer:\\n   447→   - **Manual-co